>  Yea, I think ideally if a buffer is deleted or becomes invalid in one autocommand then later autocommands shouldn't fire at all.

Looking at the source code, it looks like it does attempt to do this already but only for buffer-local autocmds.

```c
bool close_buffer(win_T *win, buf_T *buf, int action, bool abort_if_last, bool ignore_abort)
{
  ...
  // Remove the buffer from the list.
  if (wipe_buf) {
    ...
    free_buffer(buf);
  }
  ...
}

/// Free a buffer structure and the things it contains related to the buffer
/// itself (not the file, that must have been done already).
static void free_buffer(buf_T *buf)
{
  ...
  aubuflocal_remove(buf);
  ...
}

// Called when buffer is freed, to remove/invalidate related buffer-local autocmds.
void aubuflocal_remove(buf_T *buf)
{
  // invalidate currently executing autocommands
  for (AutoPatCmd *apc = active_apc_list; apc != NULL; apc = apc->next) {
    if (buf->b_fnum == apc->arg_bufnr) {
      apc->arg_bufnr = 0;
    }
  }
  ...
}
```
